      <h1>About this calculator</h1>
      <p>
        This site helps homeowners ballpark a generator size using a simplified interpretation of the
        National Electrical Code (NEC) dwelling load method, tailored for
        <strong> residential optional standby systems</strong>.
      </p>

      <h2>How the calculator works (high level)</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>General lighting load:</strong> 3&nbsp;VA/ft² of floor area you enter.</li>
        <li><strong>Small appliance &amp; laundry circuits:</strong> 1,500&nbsp;VA each.</li>
        <li><strong>Fixed appliances:</strong> nameplate running watts at 100%.</li>
        <li><strong>Demand factor:</strong> first 10&nbsp;kVA at 100%, remainder at 40% for non-A/C portion.</li>
        <li><strong>Cooling vs heating:</strong> larger of A/C or heat added at 100% (with special handling for heat pumps + strip heat).</li>
        <li><strong>EV charging:</strong> Level 2 loads added at 100% based on breaker size.</li>
        <li><strong>Headroom:</strong> default 20% safety factor before rounding to a common generator size.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What this site is (and isn’t)</h2>
      <p>
        This tool is oriented to <strong>residential optional standby systems</strong> (NEC Article&nbsp;702).
        It is <em>not</em> intended for
        <strong> emergency systems</strong> (Article&nbsp;700),
        <strong> legally required standby</strong> (Article&nbsp;701), or
        <strong> critical operations power systems</strong> (Article&nbsp;708), which have different requirements.
      </p>
      <p>
        It’s planning guidance, not a site survey. Homes vary, nameplates can surprise, and local AHJs may amend the NEC.
        Before purchasing or installing a generator, <strong>consult a licensed electrician/contractor</strong> and your utility to
        confirm sizing, transfer equipment, interconnection rules, and code compliance.
      </p>

